Part 1: Data

The data involved in this project is said to be derived from 651 randomly selected sampled movies produced and released before 2016. Considering that 651 movies is less than 10% of all movies produced and released before 2016 and that the samples were chosen randomly, independence and generalizability is acceptable. However, since the data is from observational methods and that there was no random assignment for control and treatment group, causation cant be inferred.

Part 2: Research question

Entertainment has been an intergral part of society, and throughout the years, it has changed and will continue to change with the constant evolution of society. While entertainment is perhaps one of the most important avenues for creative expression and development, one might argue that the value of entertainment stems from the fact that it provides a temporary respite from the rigors of real life. As such, the audience not only can appreciate the talent and the work involved in making one form of entertainment (e.g.movie, TV show, concert), but can also suspend his/her thoughts or concerns in his/her own life while getting immersed on the experience. As a result, entertainment can have some form or degree of emotional effect to its audience. Such an effect can contribute towards how popular or well-received an entertainment event could be.

Movies, in particular, involve a lot of resources and investment. One such resource that involves both the movie makers and the audience is time. Movie makers might consider on whether a great movie has to be short or long. This is important since a shorter movie usually requires lesser resources and expense than a longer one. In the perspective of the audience, a long movie, depending on other factors as well, can be dragging, resulting to a less pleasuarble experience. In the same sense, a shorter one can potentially leave out important scences that prevent audiences from establishing a deeper connection with the movies entirety. Therefore, the main question for this project is: Is there an association between movie popularity (audience_score) and movie length (runtime)?

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

From the data taken from the IMDB and Rotten Tomatoes, only imdb_rating, critics_score, and audience_score variables can be used to represent the popularity of movies. Among the three, the audience_score is chosen to be the response variable since it is derived mainly from the input of the audience and not from professional critics who may have more skill and knowledge in evaluating movies. To answer the research question, the variable runtime will be the predictor variable.After going through the rest of the variables, the following variables can have potential effects on the response variables (imdb_rating, critics_score, and audience_score), and therefore considered as explanatory or predictor variables: genre, runtime, mpaa_rating, imdb_num_votes, critics_rating, best_pic_nom, best_pic_win, best_actor_win, best_actress_win, and best_dir_win. While the variable top200_box may seem relevant, it is more likely the result of the movies popularity rather than a contributing factor, so therefore it was not considered as one of the explanatory or predictor variables.

Basing on the above explanation, a new dataframe was formed with the needed variables.

As evident in the scatterplot, majority of the movies are located between 90 to 140 minutes with a wide variability in their respective audience score. This indicates a weak association between the two variables. To formally determine this, a linear regression was performed.

a <- lm(audience_score ~ runtime, data = movies1)
summary(a)

Basing on the results, the correlation between the movie runtimes and audience score is positive but not strong. With an R squared = 0.03275 (R = 0.18), only 3% of the variability of the audience_score can be explained by the movies runtimes. Still it is significant as indicated by the very low p-value (3.431e-06). The model for this association is:

audience_score = 42.4203 + (0.1883)runtime

Overlaying the model on the scatterplot shows:

aud_time_plot + geom_smooth(method = lm)

Overall, a movies runtime is not strong predictor for its popularity. Other aspects of the movies whether as individual or in combinations can provide better predictions for the movie popularity.

Part 4: Modeling

In order to arrive at a linear model that provides the best possible prediction to a movies popularity, relevant variables should only be considered. Such variables should represent its potential contribution to the quality of the movie and therefore to the quality of the experience of the audience. The ability of the actors and actresses to effectively portray their respective character is tantamount to a good movie. Therefore, the variables best_actor_win and best_actress_win are included. Having an excellent director is also important for a great movie, so the variable best_dir_win is also included. The critics_score is also included since the scores are derived from designated or even professional movie critics and reviewers. The imdb_rating however is not included since it represents input from both audience and critics, therefore potentially providing colinearity with the critics_score and the audience_score, which is the response variable.

The rest of the variables are excluded since some either dont provide relevant information for the movies popularity (e.g.genre, title_type, mpaa_rating, release dates, names) or provide parallel results from that of the included variables (e.g.critics_rating, audience_rating).

Therefore the response variable for the model is the audience_score while the predictor variables included are critics_score, best_actor_win, best_actress_win, and best_dir_win. A backwards R squared method was used since the intention is to arrive on a model with more reliable predictors. A full model was then formed.

full_model <- lm(audience_score ~ critics_score + 
                                   best_actor_win +
                                   best_actress_win +
                                   best_dir_win, data = movies1)
summary(full_model)

With a very small p-value, the model is significant and that at least one variable is a significant predictor for the response variable. Basing on the p-values of the coefficients, only the critics_score provided statistically significant results. If the p-value method was used, the resulting model would be:

audience_score = 33.19 + 0.5(critics_score)

The diagnostics revealed that the model is strong since the correlation is linear, the points in the Residual vs Fitted plot are randomly distributed, and the Normal Q-Q plot indicates a normal distribution of the residuals

Part 5: Prediction

For prediction using the newly formed model, I will be using the information on the movie Jason Bourne(2016). According to Rotten Tomatoes (https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/jason_bourne) the critics score for this movie is 56%. Using the model: audience_score = 33.19 + 0.5(critics_score), the predicted audience score is:

critic <- data.frame(critics_score = 56)
predict(final_mod, newdata = critic, interval = "prediction")
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 61.51601 33.28163 89.75039

The predicted audience score of 61.51601 is actually close to the actual audience score of 61. Also, we can 95% confident that the predicted value will fall between 33.28163 and 89.75039.

Part 6: Conclusion

While most people base their decisions to watch a particular movie on other factors such as the actors and actresses involved, the director that orchestrated the movie, the premise of the movies storyline, and perhaps the quality of its promotional materials, data from this project supports that the Critics Score in Rotten Tomatoes can be used to predict the audience enjoyment of a particular movie and therefore the movies eventual popularity. This is understandable since such critics are more likely to be more adept in identifying details that could make a good movie.
